  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "From Orchomenus
    Plutarch in his ‘Banquet of the Seven Sages has C. taking part in the conversations as a poet (Mor. 156f), contemporary and 
    close friend of Periander, tyrant of Corinth (end of the 7th/beginning 6th cent. BC). Two hexameters by the poet (Paus. 9,38,9),
    in which the city's hero Aspledon is described as the son of Poseidon and Midea, are supposed to attest to the accuracy of local 
    tradition in the Boeotian city of the same name...." from Selzer, Christoph (Frankfurt/Main).
    "Chersias." Brill’s New Pauly. Brill Online, 2013. Reference. Tufts University Library. 27 March 2013 .</mads:note>
